<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="453" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1757,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">
In the classification of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[410,572,1793,1819]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Schindleriidae</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[846,949,1793,1819]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Gobiidae</taxonomicName>
we follow 
<bibRefCitation author="Thacker, C. E." box="[1077,1253,1793,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="93 - 104" refId="ref13786" refString="Thacker, C. E. (2009) Phylogeny of Gobioidei and placement within Acanthomorpha, with a new classification and investigation of diversification and character evolution. Copeia, 2009, 93 - 104. https: // doi. org / 10.1643 / CI- 08 - 004" type="journal article" year="2009">Thacker (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, a view adopted by several authors (
<bibRefCitation author="Gill, A. C. &amp; Mooi, R. D." box="[370,578,1829,1856]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="51 - 59" refId="ref12108" refString="Gill, A. C. &amp; Mooi, R. D. (2010) Character evidence for the monophyly of Microdesminae, with comments on relationships to Schindleria (Teleostei: Gobioidei: Gobiidae). Zootaxa, 2442 (1), 51 - 59. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2442.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">Gill &amp; Mooi 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Betancur-R, R. &amp; Wiley, E. O. &amp; Arratia, G. &amp; Acero, A. &amp; Bailly, N. &amp; Miya, M. &amp; Lecointre, G. &amp; Orti, G." box="[589,848,1829,1856]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="162" refId="ref11523" refString="Betancur-R, R., Wiley, E. O., Arratia, G., Acero, A., Bailly, N., Miya, M., Lecointre, G. &amp; Orti, G. (2017) Phylogenetic classification of bony fishes. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 17, 162. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12862 - 017 - 0958 - 3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Betancur-R 
<emphasis box="[725,781,1829,1855]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1757,2036]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,153,828]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="453" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">
Six nominal species of Schindler’s fishes are documented, four from the Pacific and two from the Indian Ocean (Red Sea) (
<bibRefCitation author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Sauberer, M." box="[282,570,1901,1928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="95 - 108" refId="ref11356" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Sauberer, M. (2018) A new species of Schindler's fish (Teleostei: Gobiidae: Schindleria) from the Malay Archipelago (Southeast Asia), with notes on the caudal fin complex of Schindleria. Zootaxa, 4531 (1), 95 - 108. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4531.1.4" type="journal article" year="2018">Ahnelt &amp; Sauberer 2018</bibRefCitation>
). But the number of species is obviously underestimated. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kon, T. &amp; Yoshino, T. &amp; Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M." box="[1238,1432,1901,1928]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="53 - 62" refId="ref12605" refString="Kon, T., Yoshino, T., Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M. (2007) DNA sequences identify numerous cryptic species of the vertebrate: A lesson from the gobioid fish Schindleria. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 44, 53 - 62. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.12.007" type="journal article" year="2007">
Kon 
<emphasis box="[1296,1355,1901,1927]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">et al.</emphasis>
(2007
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kon, T. &amp; Yoshino, T. &amp; Nishida, M." box="[151,208,1938,1964]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="62 - 66" refId="ref12669" refString="Kon, T., Yoshino, T. &amp; Nishida, M. (2011) Cryptic species of the gobioid paedomorphic genus Schindleria from Palau, western Pacific Ocean. Ichthyological Research, 58, 62 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10228 - 010 - 0178 - y" type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
) found more than 30 cryptic species just in the western Pacific. Separation of these extremely paedomorphic species based on morphological characters is challenging (
<bibRefCitation author="Kon, T. &amp; Yoshino, T. &amp; Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M." box="[805,984,1973,2000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="53 - 62" refId="ref12605" refString="Kon, T., Yoshino, T., Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M. (2007) DNA sequences identify numerous cryptic species of the vertebrate: A lesson from the gobioid fish Schindleria. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 44, 53 - 62. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.12.007" type="journal article" year="2007">
Kon 
<emphasis box="[862,911,1973,1999]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Sauberer, M." box="[994,1271,1973,2000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="95 - 108" refId="ref11356" refString="Ahnelt, H. &amp; Sauberer, M. (2018) A new species of Schindler's fish (Teleostei: Gobiidae: Schindleria) from the Malay Archipelago (Southeast Asia), with notes on the caudal fin complex of Schindleria. Zootaxa, 4531 (1), 95 - 108. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4531.1.4" type="journal article" year="2018">Ahnelt &amp; Sauberer 2018</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ahnelt, H." box="[1281,1425,1973,2000]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="450 - 456" refId="ref11305" refString="Ahnelt, H. (2019) Redescription of the paedomorphic goby Schindleria nigropunctata Fricke &amp; El-Regal 2017 (Teleostei: Gobiidae) from the Red Sea. Zootaxa, 4615 (3), 450 - 456. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4615.3.2" type="journal article" year="2019">Ahnelt 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The most striking difference between the first described species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[894,1023,2009,2035]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[894,1023,2009,2035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">Schindleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schindler 1930)" baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[1036,1390,2009,2036]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="praematura">
<emphasis box="[1036,1195,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="452">S. praematura</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schindler, O." box="[1209,1381,2009,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="452" pagination="79 - 80" refId="ref13610" refString="Schindler, O. (1930) Ein neuer Hemirhamphus aus dem Pazifischen Ozean. Anzeiger der Akademie der Wissenschaften Wien, 67, 79 - 80." type="journal article" year="1930">Schindler 1930</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schindler 1931)" baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[151,526,153,179]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis box="[151,328,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schindler, O." box="[343,518,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="2 - 3" refId="ref13638" refString="Schindler, O. (1931) Ein neuer Hemirhamphus aus dem Pazifischen Ozean. Anzeiger der Akademie der Wissenschaften Wien, 68, 2 - 3." type="journal article" year="1931">Schindler 1931</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, was the relative positions of the dorsal and anal fins: in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[1161,1321,153,179]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="praematura">
<emphasis box="[1161,1321,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. praematura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the origin of the dorsal fin is well in advance of the origin of the anal fin, while in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[987,1165,189,215]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis box="[987,1165,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the origin of the dorsal fin is just above the origin of the anal fin (
<bibRefCitation author="Schindler, O." box="[641,818,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="79 - 80" refId="ref13610" refString="Schindler, O. (1930) Ein neuer Hemirhamphus aus dem Pazifischen Ozean. Anzeiger der Akademie der Wissenschaften Wien, 67, 79 - 80." type="journal article" year="1930">Schindler 1930</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schindler, O." box="[832,891,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="2 - 3" refId="ref13638" refString="Schindler, O. (1931) Ein neuer Hemirhamphus aus dem Pazifischen Ozean. Anzeiger der Akademie der Wissenschaften Wien, 68, 2 - 3." type="journal article" year="1931">1931</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, G. D. &amp; Brothers, E. B." box="[904,1201,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="441 - 471" refId="ref12430" refString="Johnson, G. D. &amp; Brothers, E. B. (1993) Schindleria: a paedomorphic goby (Teleostei: Gobioidei). Bulletin of Marine Science, 52, 441 - 471." type="journal article" year="1993">Johnson &amp; Brothers 1993</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequently most authors followed this character and consequently named specimens from their samples either 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[1214,1375,261,287]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="praematura">
<emphasis box="[1214,1375,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. praematura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
depending on the relative fin position.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,153,828]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
We checked 49 publications (72 records) which reported findings of Schindler’s fishes (
<tableCitation box="[1209,1295,333,359]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,874,898]" captionTargetBox="[166,1313,982,1990]" captionText="TABLE 1. 72 records from 49 publications, including the publications of the six formally described species of Schindleria (highlighted in grey). * refers to the type specimens of S. nigropunctata, actually a LDF type, and therefore listed twice. Nominal species highlighted in grey. List of references see below." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0AE96659417EFFAFFF76FCD177EEA0FA" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" tableUuid="0AE96659417EFFAFFF76FCD177EEA0FA">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Excluding those publications which formally described a species (n = 6), the remaining 43 studies comprised 65 records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[151,280,405,431]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,280,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Schindleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In 41 of these records the specimens were identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[932,1094,405,431]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="praematura">
<emphasis box="[932,1094,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. praematura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in 14 as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[1208,1387,405,431]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis box="[1208,1387,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in two as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson &amp; Walker" authorityYear="2004" box="[266,435,441,467]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis box="[266,435,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Eight of the records were not assigned to a species and were identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[1307,1436,441,467]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1307,1436,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">Schindleria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[222,388,477,503]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Schindleriidae</taxonomicName>
. In the light of high endemism and a large number of cryptic species (
<bibRefCitation author="Kon, T. &amp; Yoshino, T. &amp; Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M." box="[1180,1362,477,503]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="53 - 62" refId="ref12605" refString="Kon, T., Yoshino, T., Mukai, T. &amp; Nishida M. (2007) DNA sequences identify numerous cryptic species of the vertebrate: A lesson from the gobioid fish Schindleria. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 44, 53 - 62. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.12.007" type="journal article" year="2007">
Kon 
<emphasis box="[1238,1295,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kon, T. &amp; Yoshino, T. &amp; Nishida, M." box="[1374,1432,477,503]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="62 - 66" refId="ref12669" refString="Kon, T., Yoshino, T. &amp; Nishida, M. (2011) Cryptic species of the gobioid paedomorphic genus Schindleria from Palau, western Pacific Ocean. Ichthyological Research, 58, 62 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10228 - 010 - 0178 - y" type="journal article" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bogorodsky, S. &amp; Randall, J. E." box="[151,476,513,539]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" pagination="239 - 265" refId="ref11598" refString="Bogorodsky, S. &amp; Randall, J. E. (2019) Endemic fishes of the Red Sea. In: Rasul, N. M. A. &amp; Stewart, I. C. F. (Eds.), Oceanographic and Biological Aspects of the Red Sea. Springer Oceanography, pp. 239 - 265. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 3 - 319 - 99417 - 8 _ 14" type="book chapter" year="2019">Bogorodsky &amp; Randall 2019</bibRefCitation>
) it is unlikely that all these documented records of Schindler’s fishes belong to one of these two species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Randall, J. E." box="[360,528,549,575]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" refId="ref13515" refString="Randall, J. E. (2007) Reef and shore fishes of the Hawaiian Islands. University of Hawai'i Sea Grant College Program, Hono- lulu, 546 pp." type="book" year="2007">Randall (2007)</bibRefCitation>
concluded that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[706,866,549,575]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="praematura">
<emphasis box="[706,866,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. praematura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schindler" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[921,1098,549,575]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pietschmanni">
<emphasis box="[921,1098,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. pietschmanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are endemic for the Hawaiian Islands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,153,828]" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
It will require a series of integrative studies including ecology, genetics and morphology just to get an overview of the number of species of 
<emphasis box="[464,600,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giltay" authorityYear="1934" box="[464,596,657,683]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Schindleria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which possibly number several dozen. Species with very distinct morphological characters like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Watson &amp; Walker" authorityYear="2004" box="[407,575,693,719]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Schindleriidae" genus="Schindleria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevipinguis">
<emphasis box="[407,575,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="453">S. brevipinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(tiny and toothless) or 
